\begin_layout Abstract

\series bold
Abstract
\series default
 The MIZ
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Main concept: the marginal ice zone in Antarctic sea ice is inextricably
 linked to the seasonal ice zone during the advancement phase.
 There is also an issue of nomenclature: new, young and first-year ice
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the Antarctic, the MIZ is a characteristic of the advancing edge, since
 during this phase sea ice progresses northwards and expands zonally due
 to the increase in ocean surface towards the equator.
 Hence, the MIZ can be depicted as a band of young ice that is continuously
 affected by air-sea interactions, in the form of heat exchanges, wind and
 current drag, and wave action.
 Every latitude of the Southern Ocean will have a period of time in which
 it can be classified as MIZ
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first two mechanisms are at play everywhere in the sea ice.
 They are however dampened because of the consolidated ice conditions and
 the presence of snow that isolates the thinner ice from the atmosphere
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This feature is found in the Arctic only in the Bering Sea and in the Greenland
 and Norwegian Seas (Wadhams book).
 During the retreat, conditions are more similar to the Arctic: the progressive
 melting and the breaking of ice floes increase the effectiveness of the
 boundary layer processes, which rearrange the pack ice into open drift
 conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sea-ice concentration (SIC), the fraction of ice-covered water, is measured
 at the Earth observation scale through the use of satellites equipped with
 passive microwaves (PM) sensors.
 Operationally, the MIZ is defined as that region of the sea ice where SIC
 is comprised between 15 and 80% 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "comisoConcentrationGradientsGrowth1984,meierComparisonSeaiceExtent2008,strongArcticMarginalIce2013,stroeveMappingAssessingVariability2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This definition is tightly linked to the SIC retrieval from satellite radiometr
y, since the limit of 15% is considered to be a viable rule-of-thumb to
 overcome the uncertainties in the methodology.
 Within this range, sea ice is assumed to be in open pack ice conditions,
 with higher chances of drifting ice and the penetration of gravity waves
 due to the floes being smaller than the wave length 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "squireOceanWaveInteractions2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This definition is operationally viable at the monthly scale in the Antarctic.
 Assuming that the sea-ice edge is traversing a region of open ocean in
 one month, this area is likely to be classified as MIZ, since it will have
 an expected SIC equal to 50%.
 This definition is therefore indicative more of the seasonal ice zone and
 the transition between new and young ice, rather than a measure of the
 MIZ, in which ocean and atmospheric processes are determinant in shaping
 the dynamics of sea ice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The assumption is that the PM-derived concentration contains information
 on the sea-ice type, which cannot however be decomposed in a particular
 category.
 The change in pixel concentration, however small, is therefore a consistent
 measure of change in ice character.
 The interest here is not whether the retrieval of brightness temperature
 is effectively measuring the concentration of ice-free versus ice-covered
 ocean, but rather if the relative change in this proxy is representative
 of a physical variation in sea ice conditions.
 This is the main concept of the method proposed here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Remote sensing data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The analysis was carried out using SIC data from the sea ice Climate Data
 Records (CDR) from NOAA/NSIDC 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "pengLongtermReproduciblePassive2013,meierNOAANSIDCClimate2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and from the EUMETSAT OSI SAF (OSI-450) product 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lavergneVersionEUMETSATOSI2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The former contains two main data sets: the official CDR from July 1987
 to December 2019, which follows all the CDR standards for traceability
 and reproducibility, and the Goddard merged product, which includes additional
 manual corrections and spatial/temporal interpolations to fill data gaps
 (extending the period back to January 1979).
 These products are very similar in terms of the longer-term properties
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "pengLongtermReproduciblePassive2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 but differ in the individual daily maps.
 The OSI-450 product is a gap-less, level 4 product, similar to the Goddard
 merged product (hereinafter NOAA/NSIDC GM).
 It extends from January 1979 through to December 2015.
 The data processing introduced an open-water filter aimed at removing weather-i
nduced false ice over open water, which unfortunately may remove some true
 low-concentration ice in the MIZ 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lavergneVersionEUMETSATOSI2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For the purpose of this analysis, which focuses on daily variability in
 the MIZ, the NOAA/NSIDC CDR is preferable since it introduces less smoothing
 and aliasing, as well as it ensures continuity with future releases of
 the data set.
 The results will be discussed against all the available data sets and the
 corresponding figures for the NOAA/NSIDC GM and OSI-450 CDR are available
 in the supplementary material.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Statistical analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The methodology treats the variability of remote-sensed SIC as if it was
 noise, a perturbation around an expected value.
 SIC is expressed as the fraction between 0 and 1 in all computations and
 figures.
 Regions of closed pack ice, or of ice-free ocean outside the seasonal ice
 zone are more likely to experience small variations around a long-term
 mean value of the SIC (close to 1 in the former case and to 0 in the latter).
 Persistent conditions of multi-year ice and permanently ice-free ocean
 will have less noise, hence a negligible dispersion around the climatological
 mean.
 The standard deviation of the daily SIC anomaly with respect to a chosen
 reference value can thus be used to measure the degree of variance in sea-ice
 conditions experienced by a certain pixel over a month.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The daily SIC anomaly 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each pixel, where the index 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 runs over the number of days in a month, is computed by subtracting the
 daily SIC from the monthly climatology.
 Since the variable SIC is constrained between 0 and 1, so is the anomaly.
 The standard deviation of the daily anomaly is then computed for each month,
 to measure the spread around the climatological SIC monthly mean as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{SIA}^{m}=\sqrt{\frac{1}{N-1}\sum_{i=1}^{N}\left(a_{i}^{m}\right)^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The index 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 runs over the total number of months in the time series.
 The standard deviation is effectively a sum of squares, since the mean
 of the anomalies is null.
 The climatological monthly standard deviation has also been computed by
 pooling together all the daily anomalies for every month in different years.
 The variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{SIA}^{m}$
\end_inset

, hereinafter referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the indicator
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, describes a left bounded distribution, where the value 0 indicates lack
 of SIC variability over the month, and the maximum expected value is 0.5.
 The exclusion of the zeroes will return an unbiased distribution of SIC
 variability, that can be characterised through the median.
 Values larger than the median are more likely to be indicative of variable
 SIC during the month.
 It should be noted that this analysis deliberately does not discriminate
 between a region that is experiencing a seasonal transition of the MIZ
 band during sea-ice advance or a persistence of short-term variable conditions
 typical of the MIZ.
 This is the main reason for using the daily anomaly against the monthly
 climatology instead of the daily climatology (based on daily values or
 daily running means over a monthly time window).
 Such a climatology would include a smooth daily transition during the advance
 and retreat phase, which would reduce the variance of the signal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the anomaly is computed roughly over the same number of days for each
 pixel (excluding the random missing data), it is more likely that a rapid
 transition between new, young and first-year ice would result in a lower
 value of the indicator.
 The median would ultimately be skewed towards the conditions of higher
 frequency of occurrence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I will discuss this choice further in Sec.
 4.
\end_layout

