\begin_layout Section
Discussion and conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
La regione marginale in Antartico e' caratterizzata da variabilita' di tipologia
 di ghiaccio, che in qualche maniera viene registrato dalle variazioni di
 concentrazione.
 The conventional method uses a concentration threshold method to identify
 regions of sea-ice cover between 15 and 80%.
 Due to the seasonal advancement and retreat of sea ice, the use of SIC
 monthly means allow to record some variability, which is then reflected
 in the overall count of pixels that can be attributed to be part of the
 MIZ 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "strongArcticMarginalIce2013,stroeveMappingAssessingVariability2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, absolute thresholds do not tell the whole story of the MIZ seasonal
 cycle, and especially they do not reflect a direct measure of variability,
 which is the ultimate feature of the MIZ.
 The proposed method allows to identify regions of higher variability and
 to quantify the climatological relative intensity.
 It gives a quantitative measure of the probability to exceed a given level
 of variation in SIC, which is obtained by computing an indicator: the standard
 deviation of the daily anomaly on a monthly basis.
 This indicator can be translated into maps of exceedance probability, hence
 giving a quantitative description of the MIZ characteristics, and not just
 a classification mask.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method does not use subjective thresholds, because the separation between
 pixels of low and high variability is obtained through a distributional
 analysis of the indicator values, which reveals a bimodal pattern.
 The percentage of exceeding a given threshold depends on the chosen value
 of the indicator, but it does not modify the relative pattern between regions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The use of a threshold-based MIZ definition leads to an underestimation
 of the ocean area that can possibly be covered by sea ice in the various
 seasons.
 In terms of the seasonal climatology, the MIZ area obtained through the
 use of a fixed threshold is underestimated in winter, and far below the
 summer area.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This may seem paradoxical, because the region classified as MIZ cannot be
 larger than the sea-ice extent.
 This is an artifact of the use of climatological means and the 15% baseline,
 which skew the distribution towards the low values, disregarding the natural
 large variability of sea ice.
 It is thus not surprising that identification of the ice edge is not carried
 out during summertime, because of the fragmentation of the ice surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The use daily of anomalies computed against the climatological monthly mean
 is justified by the 
